
âœ… What Is a Hook in React?

A Hook is simply a special function in React that lets you â€œhook intoâ€ React features (like state, lifecycle, context) inside a functional component.

Before hooks, these features were only available in class components.
Hooks made it possible to use state and lifecycle in function components.

ðŸ” Simple Definition

A Hook is a React function that starts with the word use and gives a functional component extra powers.

Examples:

useState() â†’ adds state to a function component

useEffect() â†’ lets your component run side effects after render

useRef() â†’ lets you keep values that don't cause re-renders

useContext() â†’ lets you use context

useReducer() â†’ lets you manage complex state

useCallback(), useMemo() â†’ performance optimization

ðŸ§  Why Are They Called Hooks?

Because they allow you to hook into Reactâ€™s internal system.

For example:

When you call useState(), you hook into Reactâ€™s state system

When you call useEffect(), you hook into Reactâ€™s lifecycle system

When you call useRef(), you hook into Reactâ€™s reference memory system

Hooks = function that hooks your component to React.

ðŸ“Œ Characteristics of Hooks

âœ” Must start with use (useState, useEffect)
âœ” Can only be used inside function components (not regular JS functions)
âœ” Cannot be called conditionally â€” must run on every render
âœ” React tracks them in order, like a list

ðŸŸ© Examples of Using Hooks
âœ” Using useState
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

âœ” Using useEffect
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("Runs after every render");
}, []);

âœ” Using your own custom hook

You can even create your own hook:

function useLocalStorage(key, defaultValue) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {
    return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(key)) || defaultValue;
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  }, [value]);

  return [value, setValue];
}

